Bank Churn Prediction with DNN¶

Background:¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Objective:¶

To build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether customers will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Data Description:¶

  • Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

  • RowNumber: Row number.

  • CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers.
  • Surname: Surname of the customer
  • Credit Score: Credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
  • Geography: The country to which the customer belongs.
  • Gender: The gender of the customer.
  • Age: Age of the customer.
  • Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank.
  • Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
  • NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
  • HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
  • IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer.
  • Exited: Did they leave the bank after all? Target variable.

Insights:¶

  • All numerical data, except of 'Surname', 'Geography' and 'Gender'
  • No NaN or missing values
  • Columns 'HasCrCard', 'IsActiveMember', and target 'Exited' already encoded as 0 and 1 as intergers
  • Inbalanced columns are 'Balance', 'NumOfProducts' and target 'Exited'
  • Only about 20% of the target 'Exited' did exited (to concentrate on for modeling)
  • Smiths are the most common!
  • Unique columns for all users are: 'RowNumber' and 'CustomerId'. 'Surname' is non-unique, although cannot be related to the analysis as being simpy a name.
  • Scaling is must due to very large values of some variables ('Balance, 'CreditScore') vs. others.

DNN Modeling¶

  • To handle highly-unbalanced class of 'Exited' people, class_weight hyperparameter was used in modeling. This can be adjusted with a weight up to 0.9 for the class of interest to obtain high recall scores. Although this will drop the precision. So that, building two separate models for:
    • Higher recall score and lower precision, assigning weight of 0.85 to the class of interest.
    • Lower recall and higher precision, assigning weight of 0.8 to the class of interest, which reflects more actual data distribution of only 20% exited people.
  • These models can be chosen per business needs: predict most of the exiting people, when suspecting many non-related or lose some of the exiting on predictions, but not suspecting as many non-related.

Model #1: For Higher recall (with Lower presicion)¶

Initialize and build the model¶

In [108]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(20, input_shape = (14,), activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(20, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

optimizer = optimizers.Adam(lr = 0.001)

model.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()

Identified points of improvement that were optimized:¶

  • Number of hidden layers (2)
  • Number of nodes: 20 per each layer
  • Laerning rate: 0.001 seems to be optimal (among many others i have tried)
  • Activation functions: 'relu' and 'sigmoid' for the last. Because it is binary classifiction, model can work without the activation function in the output layer, although 'sigmoid' improved the model scores.

Predicting the results using 0.5 as a threshold and accuracy score¶

In [113]:
Y_pred_cls = model.predict_classes(X_test_scaled, batch_size=1000, verbose=0)
Y_pred_cls = (Y_pred_cls > 0.5)

print('Accuracy Model (Dropout): '+ str(model.evaluate(X_test_scaled, y_test)[1]))

print('Recall_score: ' + str(round(recall_score(y_test,Y_pred_cls), 3)))
print('Precision_score: ' + str(round(precision_score(y_test, Y_pred_cls), 3)))

model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(50, input_shape = (14,), activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(50, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

optimizer = optimizers.Adam(lr = 0.001)

model.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

model.summary()

Identified points of improvement that were optimized:¶

  • Number of hidden layers (2)
  • Number of nodes: 50 per each layer
  • Laerning rate: 0.001 seems to be optimal (among many others i have tried)
  • Activation functions: 'relu' and 'sigmoid' for the last. Because it is binary classifiction, model can work without the activation function in the output layer, although 'sigmoid' improved the model scores.

Conclusions:¶

  1. First model resulted in Recall score of 84.5% with only 79 FN people (from 509) where model 'lost' them as exiting. The model precsion score is very low, only 41%, and 620 FP people (from 1991) where model 'thinks' they will exit , but they will not.

  2. Second model resulted in Recall score of 77% with 116 FN people (from 509) where model 'lost' them as exiting. The model precsion score is somewhat higher, although still only 46%, and 458 FP people (from 1991) where model 'thinks' they will exit , but they will not.

  3. Precsion can be adjusted by more equally balancing class_weight hyperparameter when training the models.

    • Business direction should identify which modeling direction to choose and what precison-recall scores are of interest.
